observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and the management agreed that:
a.	The MHRMO to:
1.	Prepare a Master List of earned leave credits of the officials and employees of the LGU as of December 31, 2024, and submit to the Local Finance Committee thru the Office of the Municipal Budget for consideration in the appropriation for the succeeding years until the earned leave credits are backed up by appropriation and funds;
2.	Prepare the quarterly leave credits earned by officials and employees, with peso equivalent and supported with a copy of its respective leave card, as of every end of the quarter, starting CY 2025; and
3.	Submit the Master list and the quarter report of earned leave credits of officials and employees to the Municipal Accountant for recording in the books subject to the availability of appropriation and funds certified by the MBO and Treasurer.
b.	The Municipal Accountant, upon receipt of the Master list and the quarter report of earned leave credits of officials and employees from the MHRMO to:
1.	Record in the books the liability duly supported by a certification from the MBO and Treasurer on the availability of appropriation and funds;
2.	In case the appropriation and funds are insufficient, continuously monitor the recognition of earned leave until such time that all earned leave credits are recorded and funded;
3.	 Ensure compliance with IPSAS 1 and IPSAS 20 by providing the required disclosures in the Notes to FS, specifically on the aggregate renumeration of key management and those who are already retired for the year and those that are retiring in the next reporting period, as well as the Municipality’s adoption of IPSAS 39 in accordance with COA Circular No. 2024-009; and
4.	Provide disclosure in the notes to FS on the nature of the leave benefits payable and its expected payment for at least the following year.

Recommendations
We recommended, and the management agreed the following:
The Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the different implementing offices with regards to project implementation under their department;
The Local Finance Committee to monitor the status of 20 per cent DF and inform the respective implementing offices for its appropriate action;
The MBO and the Municipal Treasurer/GSO to begin with the necessary steps for the acquisition of road lots for Barangay Road Development for the proposed sanitary landfill project; and
The BAC to fast-track the conduct of the necessary bidding procedures for the commencement of the project.

We recommended, and the Municipal accountant agreed to;
Reclassify the balance of Due to PhilHealth account to Due to GOCC account;
Make the necessary adjusting entry to correct the entries made;
Properly review the transactions before posting in the books of account in accordance with IPSAS No. 1, COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 and P.D. 1445.

We recommended that the:

1.Municipal Treasurer reconcile her records with the records of the Municipal Assessor for the preparation of the required list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year, Real Property Tax Account Registry (RPTAR), and certified list of RPT delinquencies;

2.Municipal Treasurer prepare, maintain and/or update RPTAR for all taxpayers based on the assessment roll/ Record of Real Property Assessment; 

3.    Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the year, a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which will serve as basis for recording of RPT and SET Receivable; and 

4.Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant undertake reconciliation of records to determine the correct balances of RPT/SET Receivable accounts and prepare necessary adjustments.

We recommended that management direct the:

1.    Heads of the custodian units of inventories held for distribution, such as the Municipal Health Office (MHO) and Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO), to prepare and maintain stock cards and other periodic report to record receipts and issuances/distributions thereof, to monitor all movements and balance of inventories within the year, and submit periodically copies of the said reports to the Property Officer for consolidation;

2.    GSO/Property Officer to assist the custodian units on the preparation of stock cards and other periodic reports and consolidate the same periodically for proper monitoring and recording of inventories held for distribution;   

3.    Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of inventories at least once a year and prepare and submit the Report of Physical Count of Inventory (RPCI) not later than January 31 of each year; and

4.    Municipal Accountant, upon receipt of the reports from the Property Unit and Inventory Committee, to make adjustments to the balances of inventory account to reflect the correct balance of inventory at the end of the year.

We recommended that the:
MA, in joint coordination with the Treasurer and Assessor, retrieve and secure at least 50% documents to be used as basis of valuation of the land account in accordance with the provisions of IPSAS 17;
MA provide this office with basis for recording the land account to ascertain whether valuation of these properties is proper and reasonable;
MA update the RPLC of all components of land account based on its accurate valuation;
GSO Designate to facilitate preparation of documentary requirements to secure the transfer certificates of titles (TCT) of untitled parcels of land to support claims of ownership;
Municipal Assessor to furnish copy of Tax Declarations and other related documents of parcels of land to GSO;
GSO update property cards of all items under land account indicating all necessary information; and
MA, GSO and Municipal Assessor reconcile their records pertaining to land account.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive
Create an Inventory Committee with adequate number of members and representatives from the Accounting and Property Division/Unit for the sole purpose of the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts of the LGU;
Temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed;
Ensure that the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided in COA Circular 2020-006 are strictly observed to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances;
Inventory Committee
Shall assign a unique Property Number for each of the PPE items of all PPE accounts of the LGU following the required code format in the numbering system as provided in Section 5 of the Circular;
Ensure that Property Stickers attached to PPE items show all vital information of the PPE as required under section 5.7 of the Circular;
Record/document the physical count daily using the ICF per PPE sub-major account group and will be the basis in the preparation of RPCPPE after the physical count;
GSO/Property Unit
Direct each office of the LGU to fill up the ICF and collect the same for verification which will then be used by the Inventory Committee as basis in the preparation of its PIP and will be considered as part of their inventory working paper;
Prepare a List of PPEs Found at Station (Annex B of the Circular) and List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) after the physical inventory and submit these lists to the Accounting Unit for recording in the books of accounts of the LGU to establish the existence and proper accountability of the PPE accounts.
Inventory Committee, Property Unit/GSO and Accounting Unit
Reconcile all records and reports pertaining to PPE after the one-time cleansing of PPE balances is successfully done and establish the correct balances of the PPE account to be recorded in the books of accounts; and
Review all documents and reports before submission to the Office of the Audit Team to ensure completeness and accuracy of details presented thereon.

Management to ensure the strict adherence to the prescribed rules and regulations on inventory under the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs effective CY 2021 and onwards and direct the:

Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of inventories at least once a year and prepare and submit the RPCI not later than January 31 of each year;

Municipal Treasurer/GSO to support each issuance of inventory with RIS and summarize them monthly in the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) which shall be the basis of the Municipal Accountant to record the appropriate expense accounts;

Municipal Treasurer/GSO to prepare and maintain stock cards to record all receipts and issuances of each item in stock; and

Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) for each inventory item as the perpetual inventory record.

The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer/GSO to:

Strictly follow the perpetual inventory method in recording and accounting of inventories for distribution;

Include the unused office supplies in the conduct of physical count of inventories for the recognition of office supplies inventory in the books;

Prepare and maintain the required forms, subsidiary records and periodic reports in relation to receipt and issuance of inventories for distribution and unused office supplies; and

Ensure completeness of details and signatories of AIR and RIS before these are attached to the disbursement vouchers.

The Municipal Accountant to:

Exert earnest effort to retrieve the necessary supporting documents of long outstanding fund transfers in order to make appropriate actions and adjustments in the books of accounts;

Facilitate the filing of request to the source agencies for authority to use the unexpended trust fund balance or transfer to the general fund, if disposition thereof has not been provided in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) and/or similar documents, as provided for under COA Circular No. 2012-001;

Prepare the necessary adjustments to correct the erroneous classifications of fund transfers and present correct balances in the financial statements. 

The Municipal Treasurer to:

Expedite the return of excess trust funds to source agencies as provided in the MOA or if the authority for the use of the unexpended trust fund balances is not approved;

The Municipal Engineer to:

Strictly monitor the implementation of projects under the trust fund and provide the Office of the Municipal Accountant the report of completion of the projects and other necessary documents in a timely manner to facilitate adjustment in the books of accounts.

Management direct the:

BAC Secretariat to post all the required information in the GPPB Online Portal for the negotiated procurement under emergency cases, if warranted, and ensure to comply with the GPPB guidelines on the posting of required information related to procurement to the GPPB Online Portal;

BAC Secretariat to ensure that Omnibus Sworn Statement (OSS) provides the date it was executed and notarized, conform with the prescribed format and submitted within the prescribed period;

Requisitioning unit and BAC to ensure complete details on the Purchase Request (PR), Purchase Orders (PO) and other supporting documents and that all needed specifications of the requisitioned items are included therein that would be useful in determining the price reasonableness and compliance with specifications;

BAC Secretariat to ensure that the suppliers/bidders properly indicate the date of receipt as they sign the NOA and the NTP; 

Municipal Accountant to review all supporting documents before processing of payment to ensure completeness thereof.

